ageant, a procession, a theatre show, a concert and a film. It contains diplomacy, politics, flag-waving (literally), sport and art. None of these are easy bedfellows, but one feels that in Danny Boyle&apos;s confident hands, the London Games curtain-raiser has a strong chance of melding those disparate elements into something intimate as well as spectacular, edgy as well as celebratory, funny as well as grand. It may even be moving.</p> <p>If the bucolic vision of rolling hills, a cricket match, 70 sheep, horses, ducks, cows and actual ploughing that Boyle has unveiled seems a little English and pastoral, rather than British and urban, I predict that surprises will be in store. From this opening scene – intended to invoke a &quot;mythic landscape&quot;, presumably on to which the actor Mark Rylance will appear to proclaim that &quot;the isle is full of noises&quot; – a &quot;thematic narrative&quot; will evolve, Boyle said, devised with the writer Frank Cottrell Boyce. According to the ceremonies&apos; executive producer, Stephen Daldry, the narrative will invoke &quot;who we were, who we are and what we will be&quot;. Both Boyle and Daldry used the word visceral.</p> <p>The terrifying splendour of the Beijing opening ceremony, with its massed ranks of highly disciplined participants, still looms large in the memory. Reading between the lines of Boyle&apos;s cryptic remarks (not unreasonably, he wants the detail of the event to unfold &quot;like a puzzle&quot; on the day), the British event will be small as well as big; invoke the individual as well as the collective; and have a touch of anarchy amid the tightly controlled choreography. He described the ceremony as like a film that will be shot live – crucially, using not only wide angles but also close-ups.</p> <p>There may be tremendous spectacle and glamour (clouds emitting rain on demand in the event that nature fails to provide; exciting aerial work from the wire strung across the stadium), but I suspect that some moments will zero in on lone figures. At the same time, Boyle is keen to make the event feel communal and inclusive, hence the two audience-filled pits beneath the twin stages, which have been dubbed the moshpit and the posh pit: one is intended to recall the audience at Glastonbury; the other reflects the other the crowd at the Last Night of the Proms. Boyle said these people would be drawn into the action of the event: &quot;You will feel very involved.&quot;</p> <p>The key to the success or failure of the ceremony is whether Boyle&apos;s integrity of vision has been allowed to remain unsullied or turns out to have been diluted by the dead hand of the committee. Boyle spoke of the many representations he had had, not just from officials but from strangers grabbing him on the tube to pass on their ideas. He had been doing a lot of listening, he said, but also noted that whatever he did he was bound to fail, to an extent: there was no way that everyone&apos;s idea of Britain could be realised.</p> <p>With luck, Boyle will have clung on to the spikiness and wit that characterises his work, alongside his gift for the spectacular visual moments that were a such an enjoyable feature of Slumdog Millionaire. He admitted that some aspects of British humour might be lost on overseas viewers, but said: &quot;I hope it will reveal how peculiar and contrary we are – and how there&apos;s also, I hope, a warmth about us.&quot; If he manages that, he will have pulled off the job.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"6291388","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-06-13T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"1758586","internalRevision":"1","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"<p><strong>Charlotte Higgins: </strong>Danny Boyle has been doing a lot of listening, but it is crucial his integrity of vision is allowed to remain unsullied</p>","allowUgc":"false","headline":"London 2012 opening ceremony promises spectacle and surprises","isInappropriateFor