event squad, who are set to be announced on Tuesday morning.</p><p>The 31-year-old, who opted out of British Fencing's \"Olympic Pathway\" two years ago for family reasons, was told in correspondence from British Fencing officials that while he was included in general discussions for selection, because the performance manager Alex Newton had not been given contact details as set out in Section&nbsp;13 of the selection policy document, he was not informed that he had not been selected and the deadline for any appeal had passed.</p><p>The chief executive, Piers Martin, explained in an email to Cook that because the Section&nbsp;13 information was not received British Fencing \"did not consider that you wanted to be considered for selection\".</p><p>Cook, ranked 95 in the world and still in the British top six having battled against recent injury, believes proper procedure was not followed.</p><p>\"I saw all these things going on in the press with people lodging appeals and I am like 'how do they know they have not been selected? What have I missed here?' Cook said. \"It was getting closer to the Olympics and I was thinking 'this is not right'.</p><p>\"I emailed the performance manager and asked to be let known what was going on because I had not received any information. I got one back saying it was to do with not giving your email address and phone number – and I said 'you must be joking'.</p><p>\"I have had constant emails, text messages and phone calls from the performance manager, I was part of the team who have been there for six years. They have got my phone number. I said 'no way are you going to do it on a technicality like that'.</p><p>\"Basically they have broken their own process. The process is that everybody is supposed to have the emails about rankings and also they are supposed to say 'have you got anything else you want to add to your case for Olympic selection?'</p><p>\"I can't argue about who they have picked because it is discretionary places, but they did not give me a chance and did not follow the process of Olympic selection.\"</p><p>British Fencing maintains its selection process is transparent and robust. The communications director, David King, said in a statement: \"British Fencing strongly denies any bias or inappropriate action in the non-selection of Keith Cook for a discretionary Home Nation place at the London 2012 Olympics.</p><p>\"British Fencing has fully supported Mr Cook in his Olympic ambitions, selecting him for every international competition where he met the qualifying standard and choosing him to participate in the Olympic test event in November.</p><p>\"Like the other 25 athletes in contention for an Olympic spot, Mr Cook would have been fully aware of what was required to achieve consideration.</p><p>\"At the time of selection Mr Cook was in 19th position across all athletes and weapons for eight host nation places. He was the sixth highest-rated men's foilist with a world ranking of 94.</p><p>\"We certainly understand the disappointment that any athlete feels when devoting one's life to training and working to achieve a goal like this and coming short.</p><p>\"While we regret that Mr Cook has felt it necessary to make these statements, British Fencing will continue to support Mr Cook's future ambitions.\"</p><p>There was some controversy surrounding the individual squad announcement at the start of June, with only two of the seven fencers having qualified by right.</p><p>King, though, added: \"We have made what we think are the best decisions, both for 2012 and 2016. We have a good squad and it is time for everyone to get behind them and let's go forward.\"</p>","internalOctopusCode":"6287668","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"true","internalPageCode":"1758252","publication":"theguardian.com","trailText":"The Scottish fencer Keith Cook has questioned the selection procedures for the GB fencing team","allowUgc":"false","headline":"London 2012: Keith Cook appeals against omissio